summary.seg: This manuscript was created in the late 13th or early 14th century. It is a compilation of legal precedents (or forms of pleading) for the drawing up of ‘counts’ or ‘narrations’, the formal statements with which plaintiffs opened their cases before the court.

Shanks recorded thirty-eight known manuscript examples of Novae Narrationes. Three distinct compilations, all probably made in the years 1285 - ca 1310 have been identified. These basic 'A', 'B', and 'C' texts were transmitted without much change, but the original arrangements of the topics differ, and copies were frequently made from two of the basic compilations: either A+B, or most commonly C+B. This manuscript appears to be a copy of an unusual form of the version C text, although it is not noted in the Shanks inventory.

This manuscript had an 18th century owner P. (T?) Wright. It was subsequently owned by Alexander Murray, Lord Henderland (1736-1795), who was a prominent Scottish lawyer and politician. Although Dupplin Castle burnt down in 1827, Murray’s library, including a fine collection of manuscripts and early printed books, survived remarkably intact. The manuscript was acquired by Trinity Hall by the 1970s.

msItem.title: Novae Narrationes
msItem.author: Anonymous
msItem.incipit: [C]eo vous moustre W. de L. (sic) par son attorney qe ci est
msItem.explicit: par R. piere laurant dit N. qui hir il est

extent.seg: ii modern parchment flyleaves + 99 folios + ii modern parchment flyleaves

layout.seg: 33–34 long lines, ruled in plummet and brown ink, catchwords, quire marks, (start of quires) running headers (most lost)

handNote.p: The manuscript is possibly written by more than one scribe. Gothic bookhand (cursive)

physDesc.additions: Occasional corrections to text, marginal headers for type of case in hand very similar to main scribe(s).

binding.p: 2007, (Cambridge Conservation Consortium) native-dyed morocco leather over wooden boards, white endbands, edges mottled red; previous 18th century binding, laced-cased, parchment over paste boards, false blue and pink endbands

history.provenance: Belonged to P.(T?) Wright Wright, P.T . His inscription: ‘Ap[ril] 11 1723. Collat. P. (T?) Wright’ is on fol. iiv, previous binding.

provenance.p: The subsequent owner was Alexander Murray, Lord Henderland, (1736–1795) Henderland Murray, Alexander, Lord, 1736-1795 . His ownership inscription: 'Dupplin Castle Library S. 184. 24’ (fol. 1r and fol. 2r. Early 19th century (inside upper cover, previous binding; Dupplin Castle, Perth); ‘B. 282’ (inside lower cover, previous binding; auction number?)

history.acquisition: Acquired by the College (details uncertain) by the 1970s

recordHist.source: Manuscript description by Dr Elizabeth New in 2009, with reference to the volume in hand.

availability.p: For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Trinity Hall Library staff.
